Note:
This file implements the main Runa lexer orchestration logic.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Orchestrate all lexical analysis components
- Manage lexer state (position, line, column, mode)
- Route characters to appropriate recognizers
- Handle whitespace, comments, and indentation
- Produce token stream for parser consumption
- Manage error reporting and recovery

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Lexer is the entry point for source code tokenization
- Proper orchestration ensures all token types are recognized
- State management is critical for accurate position tracking
- Error handling enables helpful diagnostic messages
- Integration point for all lexical components

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Lexer state management and initialization
- Character-by-character source scanning
- Token type determination and dispatch
- Whitespace and comment processing
- Aesthetic indentation tracking (consistency warnings, not syntactic)
- Error token generation and recovery
- Token stream construction

Dependencies:
- Imports ALL lexical components (literals, keywords, operators, etc.)
- Imports core/string_core.runa for string operations
- Imports core/memory_core.runa for memory management
- Imports memory/layout.runa for structure allocation
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/literals.runa" as Literals
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/delimiters.runa" as Delimiters
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/keywords.runa" as Keywords
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/math_symbols.runa" as MathSymbols
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/operators.runa" as Operators
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/encasing_handler.runa" as EncasingHandler
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/statement_patterns.runa" as StatementPatterns
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/token_stream.runa" as TokenStream
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/import_resolver.runa" as ImportResolver
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/syntax_transformer.runa" as SyntaxTransformer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrimitive
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/stack.runa" as Stack
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/diagnostics/diagnostics_engine.runa" as Diagnostics
Import "compiler/frontend/diagnostics/errors.runa" as Errors
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/token_constants.runa" as TokenConstants

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Mode Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant LEXER_MODE_CANON as Integer is 0       Note: Canon mode (natural language syntax)
Constant LEXER_MODE_DEVELOPER as Integer is 1   Note: Developer mode (symbol syntax)
Constant LEXER_MODE_VIEWER as Integer is 2      Note: Viewer mode (display-optimized)

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Control Token Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================


Note: TOKEN_INDENT and TOKEN_DEDENT are NOT used in Runa
Note: Indentation is AESTHETIC ONLY - tracked for consistency warnings, NOT syntactic like Python
Note: The lexer tracks indentation state but does NOT emit tokens that affect parsing

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer State Structure
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "LexerState":
    source_code as Integer      Note: Pointer to source code string (offset 0)
    source_length as Integer    Note: Length of source code (offset 8)
    current_position as Integer Note: Current character position in source (offset 16)
    line as Integer            Note: Current line number (1-indexed) (offset 24)
    column as Integer          Note: Current column number (1-indexed) (offset 32)
    mode as Integer            Note: Lexer mode (CANON, DEVELOPER, VIEWER) (offset 40)
    indentation_stack as Integer Note: Stack of indentation levels (offset 48)
    current_indent_level as Integer Note: Current indentation depth (offset 56)
    indent_size as Integer      Note: Number of spaces per indent level (typically 4) (offset 64)
    tokens as Integer          Note: Dynamic array of generated tokens (offset 72)
    token_count as Integer     Note: Number of tokens generated (offset 80)
    error_count as Integer     Note: Number of lexical errors encountered (offset 88)
    errors as Integer          Note: Array of error structures (offset 96)
    in_string as Integer       Note: Boolean: 1 if inside string literal (offset 104)
    in_comment as Integer      Note: Boolean: 1 if inside multi-line comment (offset 112)
    in_encasing as Integer     Note: Boolean: 1 if in variable encasing context (offset 120)
    delimiter_context as Integer Note: Pointer to DelimiterContext for bracket tracking (offset 128)
    keyword_table as Integer   Note: Pointer to KeywordTable for keyword lookup (offset 136)
    strict_mode as Integer        Note: Boolean: 1 for strict error handling (offset 144)
    allow_tabs as Integer         Note: Boolean: 1 to allow tab characters (offset 152)
    report_warnings as Integer    Note: Boolean: 1 to report non-fatal warnings (offset 160)
    preserve_comments as Integer  Note: Boolean: 1 to keep comment tokens (offset 168)
    preserve_whitespace as Integer Note: Boolean: 1 to keep whitespace tokens (offset 176)
    at_line_start as Integer      Note: Boolean: 1 if at start of logical line (offset 184)
    diagnostics_engine as Integer Note: OWNED DiagnosticsEngine for error reporting (offset 192)
    arena as Integer              Note: Arena for temporary allocations during lexing (offset 200)
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation and Initialization
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "lexer_create" takes source_code as Integer, source_length as Integer, mode as Integer, arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Create and initialize a new lexer

    Parameters:
      source_code - Pointer to source code string
      source_length - Length of source code
      mode - Lexer mode (LEXER_MODE_CANON, LEXER_MODE_DEVELOPER, etc.)
      arena - Arena for temporary allocations during lexing

    Returns:
      Pointer to initialized LexerState structure
      Returns 0 on allocation failure
    :End Note

    Note: Validate inputs
    If source_code is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL source code
    End If

    If source_length is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Invalid length
    End If

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL arena
    End If

    Note: Allocate LexerState structure (26 fields × 8 bytes = 208 bytes)
    Let lexer_size be 208
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Allocation failed
    End If

    Note: Store source code pointer and length (offsets 0, 8)
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 0, source_code
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 8, source_length

    Note: Initialize position tracking (offsets 16, 24, 32)
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 16, 0   Note: current_position = 0
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 24, 1   Note: line = 1
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 32, 1   Note: column = 1

    Note: Store mode (offset 40)
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 40, mode

    Note: Initialize indentation tracking (offsets 48, 56, 64)
    Let indent_stack be proc stack_create from Stack
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 48, indent_stack  Note: indentation_stack
    Note: Push initial indentation level 0 onto stack
    Let push_result be proc stack_push from Stack with indent_stack, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 56, 0   Note: current_indent_level = 0
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 64, 4   Note: indent_size = 4

    Note: Initialize token tracking (offsets 72, 80)
    Let tokens_list be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 72, tokens_list
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 80, 0   Note: token_count = 0

    Note: Initialize error tracking (offsets 88, 96)
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 88, 0   Note: error_count = 0
    Let errors_list be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 96, errors_list

    Note: Initialize context flags (offsets 104, 112, 120)
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 104, 0  Note: in_string = 0
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 112, 0  Note: in_comment = 0
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 120, 0  Note: in_encasing = 0

    Note: Initialize delimiter context and keyword table (offsets 128, 136)
    Let delimiter_context be proc create_delimiter_context from Delimiters
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 128, delimiter_context
    Let keyword_table be proc create_keyword_table from Keywords
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 136, keyword_table

    Note: Set default configuration (offsets 144, 152, 160, 168, 176)
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 144, 1  Note: strict_mode = 1
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 152, 0  Note: allow_tabs = 0
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 160, 1  Note: report_warnings = 1
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 168, 0  Note: preserve_comments = 0
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 176, 0  Note: preserve_whitespace = 0

    Note: Initialize indentation tracking state (offset 184)
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 184, 1  Note: at_line_start = 1 (start at beginning of first line)

    Note: Create diagnostics engine for error reporting (offset 192)
    Let diagnostics_engine be proc diagnostics_engine_create from Diagnostics with arena

    If diagnostics_engine is equal to 0:
        Note: Cleanup on failure - cascade cleanup
        If keyword_table is not equal to 0:
            Let destroy_result be proc destroy_keyword_table from Keywords with keyword_table
        End If
        If delimiter_context is not equal to 0:
            Set destroy_result to proc destroy_delimiter_context from Delimiters with delimiter_context
        End If
        If errors_list is not equal to 0:
            Set destroy_result to proc destroy from List with errors_list
        End If
        If tokens_list is not equal to 0:
            Set destroy_result to proc destroy from List with tokens_list
        End If
        If indent_stack is not equal to 0:
            Set destroy_result to proc stack_destroy from Stack with indent_stack
        End If
        Let dealloc_result be proc deallocate from Layout with lexer
        Return 0  Note: Diagnostics engine creation failed
    End If

    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 192, diagnostics_engine

    Note: Store arena reference (offset 200)
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 200, arena

    Return lexer
End Process

Process called "lexer_destroy" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Clean up and deallocate lexer resources.
    Note: Parameters: lexer - Pointer to LexerState to destroy.
    Note: Returns: 1 on success.

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: NULL lexer, nothing to destroy
    End If

    Note: Deallocate indentation_stack (offset 48) if not NULL
    Let indentation_stack be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 48
    If indentation_stack is not equal to 0:
        Let destroy_result be proc stack_destroy from Stack with indentation_stack
    End If

    Note: Deallocate tokens array (offset 72) and individual tokens if not NULL
    Let tokens be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 72
    Let token_count be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 80
    If tokens is not equal to 0:
        Note: Free each individual token
        Let token_index be 0
        Loop forever:
            If token_index is greater than or equal to token_count:
                Break
            End If

            Note: Get token pointer from array (array stores pointers, each 8 bytes)
            Let token_offset be token_index multiplied by 8
            Let token_ptr be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with tokens, token_offset

            Note: Free the token if it's not NULL
            If token_ptr is not equal to 0:
                Let dealloc_result be proc deallocate from Layout with token_ptr
            End If

            Set token_index to token_index plus 1
        End While

        Note: Free the tokens array itself
        Set dealloc_result to proc deallocate from Layout with tokens
    End If

    Note: Deallocate errors array (offset 96) and individual errors if not NULL
    Let errors be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 96
    Let error_count be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 88
    If errors is not equal to 0:
        Note: Free each individual error
        Let error_index be 0
        Loop forever:
            If error_index is greater than or equal to error_count:
                Break
            End If

            Note: Get error pointer from array (array stores pointers, each 8 bytes)
            Let error_offset be error_index multiplied by 8
            Let error_ptr be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with errors, error_offset

            Note: Free the error if it's not NULL
            If error_ptr is not equal to 0:
                Set dealloc_result to proc deallocate from Layout with error_ptr
            End If

            Set error_index to error_index plus 1
        End While

        Note: Free the errors array itself
        Set dealloc_result to proc deallocate from Layout with errors
    End If

    Note: Deallocate delimiter_context (offset 128) if not NULL
    Let delimiter_context be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 128
    If delimiter_context is not equal to 0:
        Note: Delimiter context has its own cleanup function
        Set destroy_result to proc destroy_delimiter_context from Delimiters with delimiter_context
    End If

    Note: Deallocate keyword_table (offset 136) if not NULL
    Let keyword_table be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 136
    If keyword_table is not equal to 0:
        Note: Keyword table has its own cleanup function
        Set destroy_result to proc destroy_keyword_table from Keywords with keyword_table
    End If

    Note: Destroy diagnostics_engine (offset 192) if not NULL
    Let diagnostics_engine be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 192
    If diagnostics_engine is not equal to 0:
        proc diagnostics_engine_destroy from Diagnostics with diagnostics_engine
    End If

    Note: Deallocate the lexer structure itself
    Set dealloc_result to proc deallocate from Layout with lexer

    Return 1  Note: Success
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Tokenization Entry Points
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "lexer_tokenize_all" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize entire source code into token stream.
    Note: Main entry point for lexical analysis - tokenizes all source code.
    Note: Performs Developer syntax to Canonical syntax transformation.
    Note: Parameters: lexer - Pointer to LexerState.
    Note: Returns: Pointer to TokenStream containing all tokens (Canonical form).
    Note: Returns 0 on fatal error.

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create List to collect raw tokens
    Let raw_tokens be proc create from List

    If raw_tokens is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Tokenize until EOF
    Loop forever:
        Note: Get next token (may be Developer or Canonical)
        Let token be proc lexer_next_token with lexer

        If token is equal to 0:
            Break  Note: Error occurred
        End If

        Note: Add token to list
        Let append_result be proc append from List with raw_tokens, token

        Note: Check token type
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with token, 0

        Note: Check for EOF
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Transform Developer syntax to Canonical syntax
    Let canonical_tokens be proc transform_token_stream from SyntaxTransformer with raw_tokens

    If canonical_tokens is equal to 0:
        Note: Transformation failed - use raw tokens
        Set canonical_tokens to raw_tokens
    End If

    Note: Convert List to array for TokenStream
    Let token_count be proc size from List with canonical_tokens
    Let array_size be token_count multiplied by 8
    Let token_array be proc allocate from Layout with array_size

    If token_array is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Copy tokens from List to array
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than token_count:
        Set token to proc get from List with canonical_tokens, i
        Let token_offset be i multiplied by 8
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token_array, token_offset, token
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Create TokenStream with Canonical tokens
    Let stream be proc create_token_stream from TokenStream with token_array, token_count

    Return stream
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Developer Syntax Transformation Integration
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "lexer_transform_if_needed" takes token as Integer, output_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Check if token is Developer syntax and transform to Canonical if needed.

    This function integrates the syntax transformer into the lexer pipeline.
    It checks if a token represents Developer syntax (operators like &, |, <<, etc.)
    and transforms it into the equivalent Canonical token sequence.

    Parameters:
      token - Token to potentially transform
      output_list - List to append transformed Canonical tokens to

    Returns:
      1 if token was transformed (output_list contains Canonical tokens)
      0 if token should be kept as-is (not Developer syntax)

    Side Effects:
      - If transformation occurs, appends Canonical tokens to output_list
      - Original token may be freed or reused depending on transformation
    :End Note

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get token type to check if it's a Developer operator
    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Note: Check if this is a Developer syntax operator
    Let is_developer be proc is_developer_operator from SyntaxTransformer with token_type

    If is_developer is equal to 0:
        Note: Not a Developer operator, keep as-is
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Transform the Developer token to Canonical token sequence
    Let transform_result be proc transform_developer_token from SyntaxTransformer with token, output_list

    Return transform_result
End Process

Process called "lexer_read_word_at_offset" takes lexer as Integer, start_lookahead as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Read an identifier-shaped word from the source starting at
    (current_position + start_lookahead) WITHOUT consuming any input, and
    return it as a freshly built string. An identifier-shaped word is a
    maximal run of letters, digits, and underscores. Returns the literal empty
    string when the starting character is not identifier-shaped.

    Parameters:
      lexer          - Pointer to LexerState.
      start_lookahead - Offset (from the current cursor) of the word's first
                        character. A caller positioned on "@" passes 1 to read
                        the keyword that immediately follows the marker.

    Returns:
      Pointer to a newly allocated string holding the scanned word (possibly
      empty). This is a pure look-ahead helper: the lexer cursor (offset 16),
      line (offset 24), and column (offset 32) are left untouched.
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with ""
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let length be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let scan_pos be position plus start_lookahead

    Let word be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with ""

    Loop forever:
        If scan_pos is greater than or equal to length:
            Break
        End If

        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, scan_pos
        Let is_letter_res be proc is_letter with ch
        Let is_digit_res be proc is_digit with ch

        If is_letter_res is equal to 1:
            Let ch_str be proc char_to_string from StringCore with ch
            Set word to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with word, ch_str
            Set scan_pos to scan_pos plus 1
        Otherwise If is_digit_res is equal to 1:
            Let ch_str_d be proc char_to_string from StringCore with ch
            Set word to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with word, ch_str_d
            Set scan_pos to scan_pos plus 1
        Otherwise If ch is equal to 95:  Note: Underscore
            Let ch_str_u be proc char_to_string from StringCore with ch
            Set word to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with word, ch_str_u
            Set scan_pos to scan_pos plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break  Note: End of identifier-shaped word
        End If
    End While

    Return word
End Process

Process called "lexer_word_is_block_annotation" takes word as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Determine whether a word is one of the recognized first-class annotation
    BLOCK keywords (the openers that carry a multi-line prose body terminated
    by a matching "@End <Keyword>").

    Parameters:
      word - Pointer to the candidate keyword string (the identifier that
             immediately follows the "@" marker).

    Returns:
      1 if the word names a recognized annotation block, 0 otherwise.

    This set is the complete annotation-block vocabulary from the Runa
    annotation system specification, identical to the set recognized by
    annotation_parser.annotation_kind_for_name. It deliberately EXCLUDES the
    inline memory/type tier markers (@ARC, @Owned, @Shared, @Stack, @Arena)
    and every other "@word" surface form: those remain ordinary TOKEN_AT
    operators handled by tokenize_at_operator and the type-annotation parser.
    Only block openers are skipped wholesale by the lexer, because their prose
    bodies are free text (apostrophes, unbalanced quotes, backticks, brackets)
    that must never be lexed as Runa code.
    :End Note

    If word is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Reasoning" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Implementation" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Uncertainty" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Request_Clarification" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "KnowledgeReference" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "TestCases" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Resource_Constraints" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Security_Scope" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Execution_Model" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Performance_Hints" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Progress" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Feedback" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Translation_Note" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Error_Handling" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Task" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Requirements" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Verify" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Request" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Context" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Collaboration" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Iteration" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word, proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Clarification" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "lexer_skip_annotation_block" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Consume an entire first-class annotation BLOCK at the character level,
    from the opening "@<Keyword>" through the matching "@End <Keyword>"
    terminator, emitting NO tokens. The lexer cursor (offset 16), line
    (offset 24), and column (offset 32) are advanced past the closing
    terminator's keyword. Mirrors the stage1 monolith's annotation handling
    (lexer.runa: skip @Reasoning ... @End Reasoning wholesale) so the parser
    never sees the prose body.

    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState positioned with the cursor on the opening
              "@" of a recognized annotation block (as confirmed by
              lexer_word_is_block_annotation on the following word).

    Returns:
      1 once the block (including its "@End <Keyword>" closer, if present) has
      been consumed. On reaching end-of-source before a closer the cursor is
      left at end-of-source and 1 is still returned (an unterminated block at
      EOF simply consumes the remaining input, exactly as the monolith does).

    Robustness: the body is scanned byte-by-byte and is NEVER tokenized as
    Runa code, so apostrophes (monolith's), unbalanced double quotes, backticks,
    brackets, colons, and any other prose punctuation in the annotation body
    cannot derail lexing. The scan terminates only on an "@" immediately
    followed by the word "End".
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let length be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Skip the opening "@" and its keyword word so an "@End" appearing as
    Note: the opener itself can never be mistaken for the terminator.
    Set position to position plus 1
    Set column to column plus 1
    Loop forever:
        If position is greater than or equal to length:
            Break
        End If
        Let okch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
        Let ok_letter be proc is_letter with okch
        Let ok_digit be proc is_digit with okch
        If ok_letter is equal to 1:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        Otherwise If ok_digit is equal to 1:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        Otherwise If okch is equal to 95:  Note: Underscore
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Scan the body until the matching "@End" terminator or end-of-source.
    Let scanning be 1
    Loop forever:
        If scanning is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        If position is greater than or equal to length:
            Set scanning to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position

            If ch is equal to 10:  Note: Newline — track line/column.
                Set line to line plus 1
                Set column to 1
                Set position to position plus 1
            Otherwise If ch is equal to 64:  Note: "@" — possible terminator.
                Note: Peek the word after this "@" to test for "End".
                Let after_at be position plus 1
                Let w0 be 0
                Let w1 be 0
                Let w2 be 0
                Let w3 be 0
                If after_at is less than length:
                    Set w0 to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, after_at
                End If
                If after_at plus 1 is less than length:
                    Set w1 to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, after_at plus 1
                End If
                If after_at plus 2 is less than length:
                    Set w2 to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, after_at plus 2
                End If
                If after_at plus 3 is less than length:
                    Set w3 to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, after_at plus 3
                End If

                Note: "End" exactly: 'E'(69) 'n'(110) 'd'(100) followed by a
                Note: non-identifier character (so "End_X"/"Ended" do not match).
                Let is_end be 0
                If w0 is equal to 69:
                    If w1 is equal to 110:
                        If w2 is equal to 100:
                            Let w3_letter be proc is_letter with w3
                            Let w3_digit be proc is_digit with w3
                            If w3_letter is equal to 0:
                                If w3_digit is equal to 0:
                                    If w3 is not equal to 95:
                                        Set is_end to 1
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If

                If is_end is equal to 1:
                    Note: Consume "@End".
                    Set position to position plus 4
                    Set column to column plus 4

                    Note: Skip spaces/tabs between "End" and the closer keyword.
                    Loop forever:
                        If position is greater than or equal to length:
                            Break
                        End If
                        Let sep be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
                        If sep is equal to 32:  Note: Space
                            Set position to position plus 1
                            Set column to column plus 1
                        Otherwise If sep is equal to 9:  Note: Tab
                            Set position to position plus 1
                            Set column to column plus 1
                        Otherwise:
                            Break
                        End If
                    End While

                    Note: Consume the closer keyword (letters/digits/underscore).
                    Loop forever:
                        If position is greater than or equal to length:
                            Break
                        End If
                        Let kch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
                        Let k_letter be proc is_letter with kch
                        Let k_digit be proc is_digit with kch
                        If k_letter is equal to 1:
                            Set position to position plus 1
                            Set column to column plus 1
                        Otherwise If k_digit is equal to 1:
                            Set position to position plus 1
                            Set column to column plus 1
                        Otherwise If kch is equal to 95:  Note: Underscore
                            Set position to position plus 1
                            Set column to column plus 1
                        Otherwise:
                            Break
                        End If
                    End While

                    Set scanning to 0
                Otherwise:
                    Note: A bare "@" inside prose (e.g. "@PLT", "@function"): consume one byte and continue.
                    Set position to position plus 1
                    Set column to column plus 1
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Set position to position plus 1
                Set column to column plus 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Commit the advanced cursor/line/column back to the lexer state.
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 24, line
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 32, column

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "lexer_next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 
    Get next token from source code
    
    Core tokenization function - dispatches to appropriate recognizer
    
    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState
    
    Returns:
      Pointer to next Token (or TOKEN_EOF/TOKEN_ERROR)
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: AESTHETIC INDENTATION TRACKING - Does NOT generate tokens
    Note: Indentation is tracked for consistency warnings only, NOT for syntax
    Note: Check if at start of line and track indentation (offset 184)
    Let at_line_start be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 184
    If at_line_start is equal to 1:
        Note: Clear the at_line_start flag
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 184, 0

        Note: Calculate current indentation level
        Let position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
        Let saved_position be position
        Let current_line be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 24
        Let current_column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32

        Note: Count spaces at start of line
        Let space_count be 0
        Let source be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 0
        Let length be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 8

        Loop forever:
            If position is greater than or equal to length:
                Break
            End If
            Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
            If ch is equal to 32:  Note: Space
                Set space_count to space_count plus 1
                Set position to position plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While

        Note: Restore position (whitespace will be skipped later)
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 16, saved_position

        Note: Calculate indent level
        Let indent_size be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 64
        Let new_indent_level be space_count divided by indent_size

        Note: Check for inconsistent indentation (not a multiple of indent_size)
        Let expected_spaces be new_indent_level multiplied by indent_size
        If space_count is not equal to expected_spaces:
            If space_count is greater than 0:
                Note: Inconsistent indentation - generate warning
                Let warning_msg be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Inconsistent indentation: "
                Let spaces_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrimitive with space_count
                Set warning_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with warning_msg, spaces_str
                Set warning_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with warning_msg, " spaces (expected multiple of "
                Let indent_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrimitive with indent_size
                Set warning_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with warning_msg, indent_str
                Set warning_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with warning_msg, ")"

                Note: Create warning error token (non-fatal)
                Let warning_token be proc allocate from Layout with 48
                If warning_token is not equal to 0:
                    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with warning_token, 0, TOKEN_WARNING
                    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with warning_token, 8, warning_msg
                    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with warning_token, 16, current_line
                    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with warning_token, 24, current_column
                    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with warning_token, 32, space_count
                    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with warning_token, 40, 0

                    Note: Add to errors list for reporting (offset 96)
                    Let errors_list be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 96
                    If errors_list is not equal to 0:
                        proc add from List with errors_list, warning_token
                        Let error_count be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 88
                        Set error_count to error_count plus 1
                        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 88, error_count
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Note: Get current indent level from stack top
        Let indent_stack be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 48
        Let stack_top be proc stack_peek from Stack with indent_stack

        Note: Track indentation changes (but don't generate tokens)
        If new_indent_level is greater than stack_top:
            Note: Indentation increased - update stack for tracking
            Let push_result be proc stack_push from Stack with indent_stack, new_indent_level
            proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 56, new_indent_level
        Otherwise If new_indent_level is less than stack_top:
            Note: Indentation decreased - pop stack to match new level
            Loop forever:
                Let current_stack_top be proc stack_peek from Stack with indent_stack
                If new_indent_level is greater than or equal to current_stack_top:
                    Break
                End If

                Note: Check for misaligned dedent (not matching any previous indent level)
                If current_stack_top is equal to 0:
                    Note: Misaligned dedent - generate warning
                    Set warning_msg to proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Misaligned dedent: indent level "
                    Let level_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrimitive with new_indent_level
                    Set warning_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with warning_msg, level_str
                    Set warning_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with warning_msg, " doesn't match any previous indent level"

                    Set warning_token to proc allocate from Layout with 48
                    If warning_token is not equal to 0:
                        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with warning_token, 0, TOKEN_WARNING
                        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with warning_token, 8, warning_msg
                        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with warning_token, 16, current_line
                        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with warning_token, 24, current_column
                        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with warning_token, 32, space_count
                        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with warning_token, 40, 0

                        Set errors_list to proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 96
                        If errors_list is not equal to 0:
                            proc add from List with errors_list, warning_token
                            Set error_count to proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 88
                            Set error_count to error_count plus 1
                            proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 88, error_count
                        End If
                    End If
                    Break
                End If

                Let popped_value be proc stack_pop from Stack with indent_stack
            End While

            Note: Update current indent level
            proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 56, new_indent_level
        End If
        Note: If indentation is equal, no tracking changes needed
        Note: Continue to normal tokenization - indentation does NOT affect parsing
    End If

    Note: Skip whitespace
    proc lexer_skip_whitespace with lexer

    Note: Check if at end
    Let at_end be proc lexer_is_at_end with lexer
    If at_end is equal to 1:
        Note: Create EOF token
        Let token be proc allocate from Layout with 48
        If token is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 0, TOKEN_EOF
        Return token
    End If

    Note: Get current character
    Let current_char be proc lexer_peek_char with lexer, 0

    Note: Determine token type
    Let token_type be proc lexer_determine_token_type with lexer, current_char

    Note: Dispatch based on type
    If token_type is equal to 1:  Note: Digit minus numeric literal
        Let start_pos be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
        Let start_line be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 24
        Let start_column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32
        Set token to proc tokenize_numeric_literal from Literals with lexer, start_pos, start_line, start_column
        Return token
    End If

    If token_type is equal to 2:  Note: String quote
        Set start_pos to proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
        Set start_line to proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set start_column to proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32
        Set token to proc tokenize_string_literal from Literals with lexer, start_pos, start_line, start_column
        Return token
    End If

    If token_type is equal to 3:  Note: Identifier/keyword
        Set token to proc lexer_tokenize_identifier_or_keyword with lexer
        Return token
    End If

    If token_type is equal to 4:  Note: Delimiter
        Set start_line to proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set start_column to proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32
        Let delimiter_context be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 128

        Note: Get delimiter type from tokenize_delimiter (returns integer token type)
        Let delimiter_type be proc tokenize_delimiter from Delimiters with lexer, current_char, start_line, start_column, delimiter_context
        If delimiter_type is equal to 0:
            Return 0  Note: Unrecognized delimiter or error
        End If

        Note: Advance past the delimiter. tokenize_delimiter classifies the
        Note: character and updates nesting context but does NOT move the
        Note: lexer cursor; the single-character delimiters routed here
        Note: (parens/braces/brackets/colon/semicolon/comma) each consume one
        Note: byte, so advance current_position (offset 16) and column
        Note: (offset 32) by 1, or the main lexer loop re-reads the delimiter
        Note: forever.
        Let delim_position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
        Let delim_column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 16, delim_position plus 1
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 32, delim_column plus 1

        Note: Get delimiter symbol string for token value
        Let delimiter_symbol be proc delimiter_type_to_string from Delimiters with delimiter_type

        Note: Create full Token structure
        Set token to proc create_delimiter_token from Delimiters with delimiter_type, delimiter_symbol, start_line, start_column
        Return token
    End If

    If token_type is equal to 5:  Note: Operator
        Set start_line to proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set start_column to proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32

        Note: Tokenize the operator. The operator tokenizers classify the
        Note: character (and any second character for multi-char operators) and
        Note: record the operator length in the token's length field (offset 32),
        Note: but they do NOT move the lexer cursor. The cursor must be advanced
        Note: here by exactly the operator length, otherwise the main lexer loop
        Note: re-reads the same operator character forever (unbounded token
        Note: allocation -> process killed). This mirrors the delimiter branch
        Note: above.
        Set token to 0

        Note: Try @ operator first (type annotation marker)
        If current_char is equal to 64:  Note: @ symbol
            Note: A first-class annotation BLOCK opener ("@Reasoning", "@Implementation",
            Note: "@Performance_Hints", "@Security_Scope", ... — the full block vocabulary)
            Note: introduces a free-text prose body terminated by "@End <Keyword>". That
            Note: body must NEVER be lexed as Runa code: apostrophes (monolith's), unbalanced
            Note: quotes, backticks, and brackets in prose would otherwise open spurious
            Note: string/char literals that swallow the "@End" closer and cascade-drop the
            Note: rest of the file. Mirroring the stage1 monolith, we skip the entire block
            Note: at the character level here and emit no token, then resume with the next
            Note: real token. Inline memory/type tier markers (@ARC, @Owned, @Shared, @Stack,
            Note: @Arena) and every other "@word" are NOT block openers and fall through to
            Note: tokenize_at_operator as ordinary TOKEN_AT operators.
            Let anno_word be proc lexer_read_word_at_offset with lexer, 1
            Let anno_is_block be proc lexer_word_is_block_annotation with anno_word
            If anno_is_block is equal to 1:
                proc lexer_skip_annotation_block with lexer
                Let after_anno be proc lexer_next_token with lexer
                Return after_anno
            End If
            Set token to proc tokenize_at_operator from Operators with lexer, current_char, start_line, start_column
        Otherwise If current_char is equal to 36:  Note: $ symbol (function pointer operator)
            Set token to proc tokenize_dollar_operator from Operators with lexer, current_char, start_line, start_column
        Otherwise If current_char is equal to 46:  Note: . — member access, range, or spread
            Note: Disambiguate by the following character: a second dot begins the
            Note: range/spread family (.. ..= ...), handled by tokenize_range_operator;
            Note: a lone dot is member access, handled by tokenize_member_access. Both
            Note: record their consumed length at token offset 32 for the cursor
            Note: advance below.
            Let dot_source be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 0
            Let dot_position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
            Let dot_peek_pos be dot_position plus 1
            Let dot_next_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with dot_source, dot_peek_pos
            If dot_next_char is equal to 46:  Note: '.' — range/spread operator
                Set token to proc tokenize_range_operator from Operators with lexer, start_line, start_column
            Otherwise:
                Set token to proc tokenize_member_access from Operators with lexer, current_char, start_line, start_column
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Note: Mathematical, comparison, logical, and bitwise operators
            Set token to proc tokenize_math_operator from MathSymbols with lexer, current_char, start_line, start_column
        End If

        If token is equal to 0:
            Return 0  Note: Unrecognized operator or allocation failure
        End If

        Note: Advance the lexer cursor past the consumed operator. The operator
        Note: length (1 for single-char operators, 2 for multi-char operators
        Note: such as **, ==, !=, <=, >=, <<, >>) is stored at token offset 32.
        Let op_token_length be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with token, 32
        If op_token_length is less than 1:
            Set op_token_length to 1  Note: Guarantee forward progress
        End If
        Let op_position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
        Let op_column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 16, op_position plus op_token_length
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 32, op_column plus op_token_length

        Return token
    End If

    If token_type is equal to 6:  Note: Comment
        proc lexer_handle_comment with lexer
        Note: Recursively get next token after comment
        Let next be proc lexer_next_token with lexer
        Return next
    End If

    Note: Unrecognized character - create error token
    Let error_msg be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Unrecognized character: '"

    Note: Append the character itself (if printable)
    If current_char is greater than or equal to 32:
        If current_char is less than 127:
            Let char_str be proc char_to_string from StringCore with current_char
            Set error_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with error_msg, char_str
        End If
    End If

    Set error_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with error_msg, "' (ASCII "
    Let ascii_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrimitive with current_char
    Set error_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with error_msg, ascii_str
    Set error_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with error_msg, ")"

    Note: Advance the lexer cursor past the unrecognized character BEFORE
    Note: producing the error token. lexer_create_error_token records the error
    Note: at the current position but does NOT move the cursor; without this
    Note: advance the main lexer loop re-reads the same unrecognized character
    Note: forever (unbounded error-token allocation -> process killed). Skipping
    Note: exactly one byte guarantees forward progress and lets lexing continue
    Note: past the offending character for error recovery.
    Let err_position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let err_column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 16, err_position plus 1
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 32, err_column plus 1

    Let error_token be proc lexer_create_error_token with lexer, error_msg
    Return error_token
End Process

Process called "lexer_determine_token_type" takes lexer as Integer, current_char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 
    Determine what type of token starts with current character
    
    Analyzes current character and lookahead to classify token type
    
    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState
      current_char - Current character (ASCII code)
    
    Returns:
      Token type category: 1=digit, 2=string, 3=identifier, 4=delimiter, 5=operator, 6=comment
      Returns 0 for unrecognized character
    :End Note

    Note: Check for digits (0-9): ASCII 48-57
    Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit with current_char
    If is_digit_result is equal to 1:
        Return 1  Note: Numeric literal
    End If

    Note: Check for string quotes (" or '): ASCII 34 or 39
    If current_char is equal to 34:  Note: Double quote
        Return 2  Note: String literal
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 39:  Note: Single quote
        Return 2  Note: String literal
    End If

    Note: Check for a Note comment BEFORE the generic identifier/keyword path.
    Note: A Runa comment opens with the exact word "Note" immediately followed by
    Note: a colon (`Note:` ... single-line, or `Note:` alone on its line ...
    Note: `:End Note` block). 'N' is a letter, so the generic is_letter check
    Note: below would otherwise classify "Note:" as an ordinary identifier (token
    Note: type 3) and the comment branch (token type 6) in lexer_next_token would
    Note: be unreachable -- every leading Apache-license `Note:` header lexed as
    Note: `Note` `:` ... which the top-level parse loop could not consume, silently
    Note: dropping the file's main Process. We require the exact 4 characters
    Note: N-o-t-e followed by ':' at offset 4 so identifiers that merely begin with
    Note: "Note" (e.g. "Notes", "Notebook") are NOT misclassified as comments.
    If current_char is equal to 78:  Note: ASCII 'N'
        Let note_c1 be proc lexer_peek_char with lexer, 1
        Let note_c2 be proc lexer_peek_char with lexer, 2
        Let note_c3 be proc lexer_peek_char with lexer, 3
        Let note_c4 be proc lexer_peek_char with lexer, 4
        If note_c1 is equal to 111:  Note: 'o'
            If note_c2 is equal to 116:  Note: 't'
                If note_c3 is equal to 101:  Note: 'e'
                    If note_c4 is equal to 58:  Note: ':'
                        Return 6  Note: Note comment (single-line or block)
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for letters or underscore (identifier/keyword start)
    Let is_letter_result be proc is_letter with current_char
    If is_letter_result is equal to 1:
        Return 3  Note: Identifier or keyword
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 95:  Note: Underscore
        Return 3  Note: Identifier or keyword
    End If

    Note: Check for delimiters (parentheses, brackets, braces)
    If current_char is equal to 40:  Note: (
        Return 4  Note: Delimiter
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 41:  Note: )
        Return 4  Note: Delimiter
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 123:  Note: {
        Return 4  Note: Delimiter
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 125:  Note: }
        Return 4  Note: Delimiter
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 91:  Note: [
        Return 4  Note: Delimiter
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
        Return 4  Note: Delimiter
    End If

    Note: Check for common operators and symbols
    If current_char is equal to 43:  Note: +
        Return 5  Note: Operator
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 45:  Note: -
        Return 5  Note: Operator
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 42:  Note: *
        Return 5  Note: Operator
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 47:  Note: /
        Return 5  Note: Operator
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 61:  Note: =
        Return 5  Note: Operator
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 60:  Note: <
        Return 5  Note: Operator
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 62:  Note: >
        Return 5  Note: Operator
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 58:  Note: :
        Return 4  Note: Delimiter (block opener / type ascription -- TOKEN_COLON)
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 59:  Note: ;
        Return 4  Note: Delimiter (TOKEN_SEMICOLON)
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 44:  Note: ,
        Return 4  Note: Delimiter
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 64:  Note: @ (type annotation)
        Return 5  Note: Operator
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 46:  Note: . (member access ".", range "..", "..=", spread "...")
        Return 5  Note: Operator
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Unrecognized character
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Whitespace and Indentation Handling
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "lexer_skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 
    Skip whitespace and track indentation changes
    
    Handles spaces, tabs (if allowed), and newlines
    
    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState
    
    Returns:
      0 (whitespace skipped, newline tracking and indentation handled)
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let length be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Track if we encounter a newline (marks start of new logical line)
    Let encountered_newline be 0

    Note: Skip whitespace characters
    Loop forever:
        If position is greater than or equal to length:
            Break
        End If

        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
        Let is_ws be proc is_whitespace with ch

        If is_ws is equal to 0:
            Break  Note: Not whitespace, stop
        End If

        Note: Handle newline specially
        If ch is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
            Set line to line plus 1
            Set column to 1
            Set encountered_newline to 1
        Otherwise:
            Set column to column plus 1
        End If

        Set position to position plus 1
    End While

    Note: Update lexer state
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 24, line
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 32, column

    Note: If we encountered a newline, set at_line_start flag (offset 184)
    If encountered_newline is equal to 1:
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 184, 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "lexer_calculate_indentation" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Calculate indentation level at current line start
    
    Counts spaces at beginning of line
    
    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState
    
    Returns:
      Indentation level (number of indent units)
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let length be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let indent_size be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 64

    Note: Count spaces at start of line
    Let space_count be 0

    Loop forever:
        If position is greater than or equal to length:
            Break
        End If

        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position

        If ch is equal to 32:  Note: Space
            Set space_count to space_count plus 1
            Set position to position plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Update position
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 16, position

    Note: Calculate indent level
    Let indent_level be space_count divided by indent_size
    Return indent_level
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Comment Handling
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "lexer_handle_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 
    Process comment (single-line or multi-line)
    
    Runa comments: "Note" ... (single-line) or "Note" ... "End Note" (multi-line)
    
    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState
    
    Returns:
      Pointer to TOKEN_COMMENT token (if comments are preserved)
      Returns 0 if comments are skipped
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL lexer
    End If

    Note: Get current position, line, column (offsets 16, 24, 32)
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let start_line be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let start_column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Skip "Note:" (5 characters)
    Let position be start_pos plus 5
    Let column be start_column plus 5
    Let line be start_line

    Note: Get source code and length (offsets 0, 8)
    Let source be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let length be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 8

    Note:
    Disambiguate single-line vs block comment.

    Runa has two comment forms. A single-line comment is the Note keyword and
    colon followed by text on the SAME line; it ends at the next newline, and
    that newline is NOT consumed (it is left for whitespace skipping and line
    tracking). A block comment is the Note keyword and colon alone on its line
    (only whitespace after the colon up to the newline), followed by body lines,
    terminated by the End-Note marker, which is consumed.

    The opening line is examined first: if any non-whitespace character appears
    after the opener before the newline, the comment is single-line; otherwise
    it is a block comment. This matches the reference compiler semantics exactly.
    :End Note
    Let is_multiline be 0
    Let end_found be 0

    Note: Scan the remainder of the opening line to classify the comment form.
    Let probe be position
    Let opener_has_content be 0
    Loop forever:
        If probe is greater than or equal to length:
            Break  Note: End of source on opening line
        End If
        Let probe_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, probe
        If probe_char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline ends the opening line
            Break
        End If
        Note: Treat space (32) and tab (9) as whitespace; anything else is content
        If probe_char is equal to 32:
            Set probe to probe plus 1
        Otherwise If probe_char is equal to 9:
            Set probe to probe plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Set opener_has_content to 1
            Break
        End If
    End While

    If opener_has_content is equal to 1:
        Note: SINGLE-LINE comment: consume up to (but not including) the newline.
        Loop forever:
            If position is greater than or equal to length:
                Break  Note: End of source
            End If
            Let sl_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
            If sl_char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline terminates the comment
                Break
            End If
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Note: BLOCK comment: scan subsequent lines until ":End Note".
        Set is_multiline to 1
        Loop forever:
            If position is greater than or equal to length:
                Break  Note: End of source (unterminated block; recovered)
            End If

            Let current_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position

            If current_char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
                Note: Advance onto the first character of the next line and keep
                Note: scanning. Every iteration advances position, guaranteeing
                Note: forward progress regardless of the body characters.
                Set position to position plus 1
                Set line to line plus 1
                Set column to 1
            Otherwise:
                Note: Check for ":End Note" terminator
                If current_char is equal to 58:  Note: Colon ':'
                    Let check_pos be position plus 1
                    Let matches_end be 1

                    Note: Check "End Note" (8 characters)
                    Let expected_end be "End Note"
                    Let check_index be 0
                    Loop forever:
                        If check_index is greater than or equal to 8:
                            Break
                        End If

                        If check_pos plus check_index is greater than or equal to length:
                            Set matches_end to 0
                            Break
                        End If

                        Let check_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, check_pos plus check_index
                        Let expected_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with expected_end, check_index

                        If check_char is not equal to expected_char:
                            Set matches_end to 0
                            Break
                        End If

                        Set check_index to check_index plus 1
                    End While

                    If matches_end is equal to 1:
                        Note: Found ":End Note" terminator
                        Set end_found to 1
                        Set position to position plus 9  Note: Skip ":End Note" (9 chars)
                        Set column to column plus 9
                        Break
                    End If
                End If

                Note: Regular character in block comment body
                Set position to position plus 1
                Set column to column plus 1
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Note: Update lexer position, line, and column (offsets 16, 24, 32)
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 24, line
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 32, column

    Note: Check preserve_comments flag (offset 168)
    Let preserve_comments be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 168

    If preserve_comments is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Skip comments
    End If

    Note: Create TOKEN_COMMENT token
    Let token_size be 48
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Allocation failed
    End If

    Note: Calculate comment length and extract comment text
    Let comment_length be position minus start_pos
    Let comment_start be start_pos

    Note: Set token fields
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 0, TOKEN_COMMENT   Note: token_type
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 8, source plus comment_start  Note: value (pointer to comment in source)
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 16, start_line     Note: line
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 24, start_column   Note: column
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 32, comment_length Note: length
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 40, is_multiline   Note: metadata (1 if multi-line, 0 if single-line)

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Identifier and Keyword Recognition
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "lexer_tokenize_identifier_or_keyword" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 
    Tokenize identifier or keyword
    
    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState
    
    Returns:
      Pointer to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER token (keyword checking deferred to parser)
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Save start position for token
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let start_line be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let start_column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Scan identifier
    Let identifier_len be proc scan_identifier with lexer

    If identifier_len is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: No identifier found
    End If

    Note: Extract identifier as a NUL-terminated heap string. scan_identifier
    Note: only returns the length; the identifier bytes sit inside the source
    Note: buffer with no terminator (the next byte is the following token's
    Note: text). The keyword lookup and the parser's declaration dispatch both
    Note: treat the token value as a C-string (hashtable_hash_string and
    Note: string_equals read until NUL), so a bare source+start_pos pointer
    Note: would hash/compare the ENTIRE remaining source ("Process called ...")
    Note: instead of just "Process" -- every keyword would miss and classify
    Note: as TOKEN_IDENTIFIER. Copy exactly identifier_len bytes and terminate.
    Let source be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let identifier_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with identifier_len plus 1
    If identifier_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let copy_index be 0
    While copy_index is less than identifier_len:
        Let src_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, start_pos plus copy_index
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with identifier_ptr, copy_index, src_byte
        Set copy_index to copy_index plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with identifier_ptr, identifier_len, 0

    Note: Check if identifier is a keyword using keyword table
    Let keyword_table be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 136
    Let token_type be TOKEN_IDENTIFIER

    If keyword_table is not equal to 0:
        Let keyword_token_type be proc lookup_keyword from Keywords with keyword_table, identifier_ptr
        If keyword_token_type is not equal to 0:
            Set token_type to keyword_token_type
        End If
    End If

    Note:
    Inline Assembly raw-body capture. When the identifier just scanned is the
    `Inline` keyword AND the following word is `Assembly`, the assembly block
    body is NOT ordinary Runa source -- it is verbatim target assembly text
    (e.g. `mov rcx, [rbp-8]`, `movzx rax, byte ptr [rcx]`, plus `#` comments).
    This two-phase lexer would otherwise tokenize that body into a meaningless
    stream of identifiers/operators/brackets that the parser cannot reconstruct
    into faithful assembly. The monolith handles this by switching to raw
    character reading after `Assembly:` (parser.runa:8254-8400). We mirror that
    here, where the live source cursor (offset 16) is available: capture the
    raw body text verbatim, advance the cursor past `End Assembly`, and emit a
    single TOKEN_INLINE token whose VALUE slot carries the raw assembly text and
    whose metadata slot carries the dialect flag (0=intel default, 1=att). The
    parser dispatches TOKEN_INLINE to parse_inline_assembly which reads these
    fields directly -- no body tokens are produced.
    :End Note
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_INLINE:
        Let asm_token be proc lexer_capture_raw_assembly with lexer, start_line, start_column
        If asm_token is not equal to 0:
            Return asm_token
        End If
    End If

    Note: Create token (48 bytes)
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with 48

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set token fields (token_type is now keyword type if keyword, else TOKEN_IDENTIFIER)
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 0, token_type  Note: token_type
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 8, identifier_ptr  Note: value (pointer to identifier in source)
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 16, start_line
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 24, start_column
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 32, identifier_len  Note: length
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 40, 0  Note: metadata

    Return token
End Process

Process called "lexer_capture_raw_assembly" takes lexer as Integer, start_line as Integer, start_column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Capture an `Inline Assembly: ... End Assembly` block as verbatim raw text.

    Called from lexer_tokenize_identifier_or_keyword immediately after the
    `Inline` keyword word has been scanned (the lexer cursor at offset 16 sits
    just past "Inline"). This procedure:
      1. Skips inter-word whitespace and confirms the next word is `Assembly`.
         If it is NOT, the cursor is restored to just-past-`Inline` and 0 is
         returned so the caller emits an ordinary TOKEN_INLINE identifier token
         (the bare `Inline` keyword in any other context is left untouched).
      2. Reads an optional dialect qualifier (`intel` or `att`) after
         `Assembly`. Default dialect is 0 (intel), matching the monolith
         (parser.runa:8264-8286) and the platform/linux_x86_64 sources authored
         in Intel syntax.
      3. Consumes the `:` that opens the block.
      4. Captures every source byte verbatim -- including `#` comments, leading
         indentation, and embedded newlines -- until the `End Assembly`
         terminator, which is recognised at the start of a line (after optional
         leading whitespace). The captured text excludes the `End Assembly`
         terminator itself.
      5. Advances the cursor past `End Assembly` so tokenization resumes with
         the statement that follows the block.

    Returns a single TOKEN_INLINE token (48 bytes) with:
      offset 0  = TOKEN_INLINE
      offset 8  = pointer to NUL-terminated raw assembly text (heap)
      offset 16 = start_line
      offset 24 = start_column
      offset 32 = raw text length
      offset 40 = dialect flag (0=intel, 1=att)
    Returns 0 if the next word is not `Assembly` (not an inline-asm block).
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let length be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 8

    Note: Remember the cursor just past `Inline` so we can restore it if the
    Note: following word is not `Assembly`.
    Let saved_position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let saved_line be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let saved_column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32

    Let position be saved_position
    Let line be saved_line
    Let column be saved_column

    Note: 1. Skip whitespace between `Inline` and the next word. Newlines are
    Note: not expected here but are handled for robustness.
    Loop forever:
        If position is greater than or equal to length:
            Break
        End If
        Let ws_ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
        If ws_ch is equal to 10:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set line to line plus 1
            Set column to 1
        Otherwise If ws_ch is equal to 32:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        Otherwise If ws_ch is equal to 9:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        Otherwise If ws_ch is equal to 13:
            Set position to position plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Scan the candidate word (letters/digits/underscore).
    Let word_start be position
    Loop forever:
        If position is greater than or equal to length:
            Break
        End If
        Let wc be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
        Let wc_letter be proc is_letter with wc
        Let wc_digit be proc is_digit with wc
        If wc_letter is equal to 1:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        Otherwise If wc_digit is equal to 1:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        Otherwise If wc is equal to 95:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Let word_len be position minus word_start

    Note: Compare the candidate word against "Assembly" (8 bytes). If it does
    Note: not match exactly, this is not an inline-asm block; restore and bail.
    Let is_assembly be 0
    If word_len is equal to 8:
        Let a0 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, word_start
        Let a1 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, word_start plus 1
        Let a2 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, word_start plus 2
        Let a3 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, word_start plus 3
        Let a4 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, word_start plus 4
        Let a5 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, word_start plus 5
        Let a6 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, word_start plus 6
        Let a7 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, word_start plus 7
        If a0 is equal to 65:
            If a1 is equal to 115:
                If a2 is equal to 115:
                    If a3 is equal to 101:
                        If a4 is equal to 109:
                            If a5 is equal to 98:
                                If a6 is equal to 108:
                                    If a7 is equal to 121:
                                        Set is_assembly to 1
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    If is_assembly is equal to 0:
        Note: Not `Inline Assembly`. Restore cursor to just past `Inline`.
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 16, saved_position
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 24, saved_line
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 32, saved_column
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: 2. Optional dialect qualifier after `Assembly`. Skip spaces/tabs only
    Note: (a dialect lives on the same line as `Assembly`), then read a word.
    Let dialect be 0
    Let dpos be position
    Loop forever:
        If dpos is greater than or equal to length:
            Break
        End If
        Let dws be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, dpos
        If dws is equal to 32:
            Set dpos to dpos plus 1
        Otherwise If dws is equal to 9:
            Set dpos to dpos plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While
    Let dword_start be dpos
    Loop forever:
        If dpos is greater than or equal to length:
            Break
        End If
        Let dwc be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, dpos
        Let dwc_letter be proc is_letter with dwc
        If dwc_letter is equal to 1:
            Set dpos to dpos plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While
    Let dword_len be dpos minus dword_start
    If dword_len is equal to 5:
        Let i0 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, dword_start
        Let i1 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, dword_start plus 1
        Let i2 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, dword_start plus 2
        Let i3 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, dword_start plus 3
        Let i4 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, dword_start plus 4
        If i0 is equal to 105:
            If i1 is equal to 110:
                If i2 is equal to 116:
                    If i3 is equal to 101:
                        If i4 is equal to 108:
                            Set dialect to 0
                            Set position to dpos
                            Set column to column plus 5 plus dword_start minus word_start minus 8
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If dword_len is equal to 3:
        Let t0 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, dword_start
        Let t1 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, dword_start plus 1
        Let t2 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, dword_start plus 2
        If t0 is equal to 97:
            If t1 is equal to 116:
                If t2 is equal to 116:
                    Set dialect to 1
                    Set position to dpos
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: 3. Skip whitespace up to and including the `:` that opens the block.
    Loop forever:
        If position is greater than or equal to length:
            Break
        End If
        Let cc be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
        If cc is equal to 58:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
            Break
        Otherwise If cc is equal to 10:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set line to line plus 1
            Set column to 1
        Otherwise If cc is equal to 32:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        Otherwise If cc is equal to 9:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        Otherwise If cc is equal to 13:
            Set position to position plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Note: Unexpected token before `:`; stop scanning the prefix and let
            Note: the body capture begin here so nothing is silently dropped.
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: 4. Capture raw body bytes verbatim until `End Assembly`. The
    Note: terminator is matched at the first non-whitespace run of a line: the
    Note: word `End` followed (after spaces/tabs) by the word `Assembly`. The
    Note: captured span excludes the terminator. We first locate the terminator
    Note: by scanning, tracking the byte offset where the body ends, then copy.
    Let body_start be position
    Let body_end be position
    Let scan_pos be position
    Let scan_line be line
    Let scan_column be column
    Let found_end be 0
    Loop forever:
        If scan_pos is greater than or equal to length:
            Set body_end to scan_pos
            Break
        End If
        Let line_first be scan_pos
        Note: Skip leading whitespace of the current line (spaces/tabs).
        Loop forever:
            If line_first is greater than or equal to length:
                Break
            End If
            Let lws be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, line_first
            If lws is equal to 32:
                Set line_first to line_first plus 1
            Otherwise If lws is equal to 9:
                Set line_first to line_first plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While
        Note: Check for `End` at line_first.
        Let is_end_word be 0
        If line_first plus 3 is less than or equal to length:
            Let e0 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, line_first
            Let e1 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, line_first plus 1
            Let e2 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, line_first plus 2
            If e0 is equal to 69:
                If e1 is equal to 110:
                    If e2 is equal to 100:
                        Note: Ensure `End` is a whole word (next char not alnum/_).
                        Let after_end be line_first plus 3
                        Let boundary_ok be 1
                        If after_end is less than length:
                            Let ae be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, after_end
                            Let ae_letter be proc is_letter with ae
                            Let ae_digit be proc is_digit with ae
                            If ae_letter is equal to 1:
                                Set boundary_ok to 0
                            End If
                            If ae_digit is equal to 1:
                                Set boundary_ok to 0
                            End If
                            If ae is equal to 95:
                                Set boundary_ok to 0
                            End If
                        End If
                        If boundary_ok is equal to 1:
                            Set is_end_word to 1
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        If is_end_word is equal to 1:
            Note: Confirm `Assembly` follows `End` (after spaces/tabs).
            Let asm_pos be line_first plus 3
            Loop forever:
                If asm_pos is greater than or equal to length:
                    Break
                End If
                Let asw be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, asm_pos
                If asw is equal to 32:
                    Set asm_pos to asm_pos plus 1
                Otherwise If asw is equal to 9:
                    Set asm_pos to asm_pos plus 1
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End While
            Let end_is_assembly be 0
            If asm_pos plus 8 is less than or equal to length:
                Let b0 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, asm_pos
                Let b1 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, asm_pos plus 1
                Let b2 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, asm_pos plus 2
                Let b3 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, asm_pos plus 3
                Let b4 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, asm_pos plus 4
                Let b5 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, asm_pos plus 5
                Let b6 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, asm_pos plus 6
                Let b7 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, asm_pos plus 7
                If b0 is equal to 65:
                    If b1 is equal to 115:
                        If b2 is equal to 115:
                            If b3 is equal to 101:
                                If b4 is equal to 109:
                                    If b5 is equal to 98:
                                        If b6 is equal to 108:
                                            If b7 is equal to 121:
                                                Set end_is_assembly to 1
                                            End If
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            If end_is_assembly is equal to 1:
                Note: Body ends at the start of this line's leading whitespace
                Note: (line_first marks the `E` of `End`). Set the cursor just
                Note: past `Assembly` so tokenization resumes after the block.
                Set body_end to line_first
                Set scan_pos to asm_pos plus 8
                Set found_end to 1
                Note: Recompute line for the resumed cursor: count newlines from
                Note: the captured body start to scan_pos.
                Break
            End If
        End If
        Note: Not the terminator. Consume the whole physical line (through its
        Note: newline) and continue scanning.
        Loop forever:
            If scan_pos is greater than or equal to length:
                Break
            End If
            Let pc be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, scan_pos
            Set scan_pos to scan_pos plus 1
            If pc is equal to 10:
                Set scan_line to scan_line plus 1
                Break
            End If
        End While
    End While

    Note: Compute the final cursor line/column by counting newlines across the
    Note: consumed region [body_start, scan_pos).
    Let final_line be line
    Let walk be body_start
    Loop forever:
        If walk is greater than or equal to scan_pos:
            Break
        End If
        Let walk_ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, walk
        If walk_ch is equal to 10:
            Set final_line to final_line plus 1
        End If
        Set walk to walk plus 1
    End While

    Note: Update the lexer cursor to just past `End Assembly`.
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 16, scan_pos
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 24, final_line
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 32, 1

    Note: Copy the captured raw body [body_start, body_end) into a fresh
    Note: NUL-terminated heap buffer.
    Let body_len be body_end minus body_start
    If body_len is less than 0:
        Set body_len to 0
    End If
    Let raw_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with body_len plus 1
    If raw_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let copy_i be 0
    Loop forever:
        If copy_i is greater than or equal to body_len:
            Break
        End If
        Let src_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, body_start plus copy_i
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with raw_ptr, copy_i, src_byte
        Set copy_i to copy_i plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with raw_ptr, body_len, 0

    Note: Build the TOKEN_INLINE token carrying the raw asm text + dialect.
    Let asm_token be proc allocate from Layout with 48
    If asm_token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with asm_token, 0, TOKEN_INLINE
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with asm_token, 8, raw_ptr
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with asm_token, 16, start_line
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with asm_token, 24, start_column
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with asm_token, 32, body_len
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with asm_token, 40, dialect

    Return asm_token
End Process

Process called "scan_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Scan identifier characters from current position

    Identifier rules: letter/underscore start, then letters/digits/underscores
    
    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState
    
    Returns:
      Length of identifier scanned (position advanced in lexer)
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let length be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let start_pos be position
    Let column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Scan while alphanumeric or underscore
    Loop forever:
        If position is greater than or equal to length:
            Break
        End If

        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
        Let is_letter_res be proc is_letter with ch
        Let is_digit_res be proc is_digit with ch

        If is_letter_res is equal to 1:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        Otherwise If is_digit_res is equal to 1:
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        Otherwise If ch is equal to 95:  Note: Underscore
            Set position to position plus 1
            Set column to column plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Break  Note: End of identifier
        End If
    End While

    Note: Update lexer position and column
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 32, column

    Note: Return length
    Let identifier_length be position minus start_pos
    Return identifier_length
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Handling and Recovery
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "lexer_create_error_token" takes lexer as Integer, error_message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Create error token and report to diagnostics system

    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState
      error_message - Description of error

    Returns:
      Pointer to TOKEN_ERROR token with error information
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL lexer
    End If

    Note: Get current line and column (offsets 24, 32)
    Let line be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Get current position (offset 16)
    Let position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16

    Note: Get diagnostics_engine and arena
    Let diagnostics_engine be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 192
    Let arena be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 200

    Note: Report error to diagnostics system
    If diagnostics_engine is not equal to 0:
        If arena is not equal to 0:
            Note: Create ErrorInfo structure in arena (15 fields × 8 bytes = 120 bytes)
            Let error_info be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 120

            If error_info is not equal to 0:
                Note: Get source file (from source_code pointer if available)
                Let source_file be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 0

                Note: Initialize ErrorInfo fields
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 0, 0           Note: error_id
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 8, 1001        Note: error_code (LEXICAL_ERROR)
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 16, 1          Note: error_type (ERROR_TYPE_LEXICAL)
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 24, 1          Note: category (LEXICAL)
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 32, 1          Note: severity (ERROR)
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 40, line       Note: line_number
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 48, column     Note: column_number
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 56, error_message Note: message
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 64, 0          Note: context
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 72, 0          Note: suggestion
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 80, 0          Note: related_errors
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 88, source_file Note: source_file
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 96, 0          Note: phase (LEXICAL_PHASE)
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 104, 1         Note: is_recoverable
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with error_info, 112, 100       Note: confidence

                Note: Collect error through diagnostics engine
                Let collect_result be proc diagnostics_engine_collect_error from Diagnostics with diagnostics_engine, error_info, 0, arena
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Create error token (Token structure: 48 bytes, 6 fields)
    Let token_size be 48
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Allocation failed
    End If

    Note: Set token fields
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 0, TOKEN_ERROR  Note: token_type
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 8, error_message  Note: value (error message)
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 16, line  Note: line
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 24, column  Note: column
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 32, 1  Note: length
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with token, 40, 0  Note: literal_metadata (NULL)

    Note: Increment error_count (offset 88)
    Let error_count be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 88
    Let new_error_count be error_count plus 1
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 88, new_error_count

    Return token
End Process

Process called "lexer_attempt_error_recovery" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 
    Attempt to recover from lexical error
    
    Recovery strategy: Skip to next whitespace, newline, or delimiter
    
    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState
    
    Returns:
      1 if recovery successful, 0 if unable to recover
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL lexer
    End If

    Note: Get current position and length (offsets 16, 8)
    Let position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 8

    Note: Skip until we find whitespace or delimiter
    Loop forever:
        Note: Check if at end
        If position is greater than or equal to length:
            Return 1  Note: Reached end, recovery by termination
        End If

        Note: Get current character
        Let source be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 0
        Let current_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position

        Note: Check if whitespace
        Let is_ws be proc is_whitespace with current_char
        If is_ws is equal to 1:
            Return 1  Note: Found whitespace, recovery successful
        End If

        Note: Check for common delimiters
        If current_char is equal to 40:  Note: (
            Return 1
        End If

        If current_char is equal to 41:  Note: )
            Return 1
        End If

        Note: Advance position
        Set position to position plus 1
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 16, position

        Note: Advance column (offset 32)
        Let column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32
        Let new_column be column plus 1
        proc memory_set_qword from Layout with lexer, 32, new_column
    End While
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Position and State Queries
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "lexer_get_current_position" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 
    Get current character position in source
    
    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState
    
    Returns:
      Current position (integer index)
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL lexer
    End If

    Note: Read current_position field (offset 16)
    Let position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16

    Return position
End Process

Process called "lexer_get_line_and_column" takes lexer as Integer, out_line as Integer, out_column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 
    Get current line and column numbers
    
    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState
      out_line - Pointer to location where line number should be written
      out_column - Pointer to location where column number should be written
    
    Returns:
      1 on success, 0 on error
    
    Memory Architecture Compliance:
      Uses out parameters instead of heap allocation for temporary return values
      Eliminates need for caller to deallocate - zero allocations, zero leaks
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL lexer
    End If

    If out_line is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL out parameter
    End If

    If out_column is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL out parameter
    End If

    Note: Read line field (offset 24) from lexer
    Let line be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 24

    Note: Read column field (offset 32) from lexer
    Let column be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Write to out parameters
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with out_line, 0, line
    proc memory_set_qword from Layout with out_column, 0, column

    Return 1  Note: Success
End Process

Process called "lexer_is_at_end" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Check if lexer has reached end of source

    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState

    Returns:
      1 if at end, 0 otherwise
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: NULL lexer is considered at end
    End If

    Note: Read current_position (offset 16)
    Let position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16

    Note: Read source_length (offset 8)
    Let length be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 8

    Note: Check if at or past end
    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 1  Note: At end
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Not at end
End Process

Process called "lexer_peek_char" takes lexer as Integer, lookahead as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
     Peek at character without consuming it

    Parameters:
      lexer - Pointer to LexerState
      lookahead - Number of characters to look ahead (0=current, 1=next, etc.)

    Returns:
      Character at position (current + lookahead)
      Returns 0 if beyond end of source
    :End Note

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL lexer
    End If

    Note: Read current_position (offset 16)
    Let position be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 16

    Note: Read source_length (offset 8)
    Let length be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 8

    Note: Calculate target position
    Let target_pos be position plus lookahead

    Note: Bounds check
    If target_pos is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0  Note: Beyond end of source
    End If

    Note: Read source_code pointer (offset 0)
    Let source be proc memory_get_qword from Layout with lexer, 0

    Note: Get character at target position
    Let character be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, target_pos

    Return character
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Utility Functions
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "is_whitespace" takes character as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 
    Check if character is whitespace
    
    Parameters:
      character - ASCII character code
    
    Returns:
      1 if whitespace (space, tab, newline, carriage return), 0 otherwise
    
    Whitespace characters: 32 (space), 9 (tab), 10 (newline), 13 (carriage return)
    :End Note

    If character is equal to 32:  Note: Space
        Return 1
    End If

    If character is equal to 9:  Note: Tab
        Return 1
    End If

    If character is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
        Return 1
    End If

    If character is equal to 13:  Note: Carriage return
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Not whitespace
End Process

Process called "is_letter" takes character as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 
    Check if character is a letter
    
    Parameters:
      character - ASCII character code
    
    Returns:
      1 if letter (A-Z or a-z), 0 otherwise
    
    Letter ranges: 65-90 (A-Z), 97-122 (a-z)
    :End Note
    
    Note: Check uppercase A-Z
    If character is greater than or equal to 65:
        If character is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check lowercase a-z
    If character is greater than or equal to 97:
        If character is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Not a letter
End Process

Process called "is_digit" takes character as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Check if character is a digit
    
    Parameters:
      character - ASCII character code
    
    Returns:
      1 if digit (0-9), 0 otherwise
    
    Digit range: 48-57 (0-9)
    :End Note

    If character is greater than or equal to 48:
        If character is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Not a digit
End Process
